s enable dynamic processor allocation. No physical fabrication required; processors exist as oscillation patterns. Demonstrates computational flexibility: arbitrary processor architectures generated by configuring oscillations. (D) Zero computation: Navigate to endpoints, don't compute. Log-log plot shows computational cost (vertical axis, $$10^0$$--$$10^6$$) versus problem size $$n$$ (horizontal axis, $$10^{-1}$$--$$10^6$$). Black diagonal line shows traditional computation: $$\text {Cost} = O(n)$$, growing linearly ($$\text {Cost} \sim 10^6$$ at $$n = 10^6$$). Cyan horizontal line shows zero computation: $$\text {Cost} = O(1)$$, constant ($$\text {Cost} \sim 1$$ for all $$n$$). Cyan shaded region (``Saved Computation'') between lines represents computational savings: area $$\sim 10^{12}$$ operations saved for $$n = 10^6$$. Zero computation navigates directly to entropy endpoints (solution states) without intermediate steps. Demonstrates exponential advantage: $$O(1)$$ versus $$O(n)$$ scaling}{figure.5}{}}
